âœ´ Kubernetes Probes are used to detect:
ğŸ‘‰ Containers that havenâ€™t started yet and canâ€™t serve traffic.
ğŸ‘‰ Containers that are overwhelmed and canâ€™t serve additional traffic.
ğŸ‘‰ Containers that are completely dead and not serving any traffic.


âœ… Liveness Probe
ğŸ‘‰ It indicates whether the container is running inside a pod
ğŸ‘‰ If the liveness probe fails, the kubelet kills the container, and the container is subjected to its restart policy.
ğŸ‘‰ If a container does not provide a liveness probe, the default state is Success.
ğŸ‘‰ If app is healthy, Kubernetes will not interfere with pod functioning. If app is unhealthy, Pod will be marked as unhealthy. If a Pod fails health-checks continuously, the Kubernetes terminates the pod and starts a new one.


âœ… Readiness Probe
ğŸ‘‰ It indicates whether the container is ready to respond to requests.
ğŸ‘‰ Readiness probes let Kubernetes know when your app (running in a container inside Pod) is ready to serve traffic.
ğŸ‘‰ If the readiness probe fails, the endpoints controller removes the Pod's IP address from the endpoints of all Services that match the Pod. 
ğŸ‘‰ Unlike a liveness probe, a readiness probe doesnâ€™t kill the container. If the readiness probe fails, Kubernetes simply hides the containerâ€™s Pod from corresponding Services, so that no traffic is redirected to it.
ğŸ‘‰ A side-effect of using Readiness Probes is that they can increase the time it takes to update Deployments.


âœ… Startup Probe
ğŸ‘‰ It indicates whether the application within the container is started.
ğŸ‘‰ Startup probe has higher priority over the two other probe types. All other probes are disabled if a startup probe is provided, until it succeeds.
ğŸ‘‰ If the startup probe fails, the kubelet kills the container, and the container is subjected to its restart policy.
ğŸ‘‰Startup probes are useful in situations where your app can take a long time to start, or could occasionally fail on startup.

